:"Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"D’Ailly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish: mainly Scottish variant of Irish   Daly  .","Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Dally   2, a cognate of 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Daly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Dermot, Brigid, Aileen, Declan, Finbarr, Fintan, Aidan, Brennan, Bridie, Cathal.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dálaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dálach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>dál</i> (modern <i>dáil</i>) ‘meeting, assembly’.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Dally   2."]},{"name":"Alyea","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>D'Ailly</b> or   Dailly  . Compare   Allee   2 and   Elyea  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with several variants, including <i>Allée</i>, and the original form <i>d'Ailly</i>). The Huguenot ancestor was Nicolas d'Ailly, who came from France to NY <i>c.</i> 1682 via the Netherlands and England and died in NJ <i>c.</i> 1700."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert D’Ailly II was born in 1268, in Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Hughes D’Ailly, was 38 and his mother, Louise Cayeux, was 25. He married Guillemette de Comminges. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1331, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1268–1331":"1268–1331","1286–1339":"1286–1339","1303–1359":"1303–1359","1305–1384":"1305–1384","1313–1364":"1313–1364","1314–1374":"1314–1374","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1243–1293":"1243–1293","1374":"1374","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1384":"1384","1293":"1293","1305":"1305","1359":"1359","1303":"1303","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1268":"1268","1331":"1331","1243":"1243","1364":"1364","1339":"1339","Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Abbeville, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1268–1331":"1268–1331","1286–1339":"1286–1339","1303–1359":"1303–1359","1305–1384":"1305–1384","1313–1364":"1313–1364","1314–1374":"1314–1374","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1243–1293":"1243–1293","1374":"1374","1286":"1286","1230":"1230","1384":"1384","1293":"1293","1305":"1305","1359":"1359","1303":"1303","1314":"1314","1313":"1313","1268":"1268","1331":"1331","1243":"1243","1364":"1364","1339":"1339","Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Abbeville, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, France":"Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Hauts-de